<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1284,2032]" box="[199,939,1608,1636]" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,288,1608,1635]" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">Colour.</emphasis>
White alive and beige to light yellow in ethanol (
<figureCitation box="[842,926,1609,1635]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1761,1786]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,166,1735]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[159,1428,166,1735]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 7. Leucascus simplex (UFRJPOR 6451). A—Specimen in situ. B—Fixed specimen. C—Cross-section of the choanosome. D—Triactine. E—Tetractine. F—Apical actine of two tetractines. Abbreviation: at = atrium; cx = cortex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3698791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3698791/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">Fig 7A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1284,2032]" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,522,1645,1671]" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">Morphology and anatomy.</emphasis>
Sponge massive, almost spherical. Sometimes there is more than one “sphere” attached to another (
<figureCitation box="[378,503,1681,1708]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1761,1786]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,166,1735]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[159,1428,166,1735]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 7. Leucascus simplex (UFRJPOR 6451). A—Specimen in situ. B—Fixed specimen. C—Cross-section of the choanosome. D—Triactine. E—Tetractine. F—Apical actine of two tetractines. Abbreviation: at = atrium; cx = cortex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3698791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3698791/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">Figs 7A, B</figureCitation>
). Each sphere has an apical osculum sometimes surrounded by membrane. The cormus is formed by regular and tightly anastomosed tubes covered by a continuous, smooth, delicate cortex. The tubes near the surface are more parallel to each other than in the middle of the choanosome. The atrial cavity is large and delimited by endopinacoderm. Aquiferous system solenoid. The skeleton is composed of triactines and tetractines (
<figureCitation box="[159,241,1825,1851]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1761,1786]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,166,1735]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[159,1428,166,1735]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 7. Leucascus simplex (UFRJPOR 6451). A—Specimen in situ. B—Fixed specimen. C—Cross-section of the choanosome. D—Triactine. E—Tetractine. F—Apical actine of two tetractines. Abbreviation: at = atrium; cx = cortex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3698791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3698791/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">Fig 7C</figureCitation>
). Triactines are more abundant than the tetractines. The atrial skeleton is composed of tetractines only.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1284,2032]" box="[199,406,1860,1888]" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,297,1860,1887]" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">Spicules</emphasis>
(
<tableCitation box="[312,397,1861,1888]" captionStart="TABLE 7" captionStartId="18.[151,239,334,358]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="TABLE 7. Spicule measurements of Leucascus simplex (UFRJPOR 6451)." pageId="16" pageNumber="277">Table 7</tableCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1284,2032]" box="[199,1367,1896,1924]" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis box="[199,311,1898,1923]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">Triactines</emphasis>
. Regular to sagittal. Actines are slightly conical with sharp tips (
<figureCitation box="[1035,1119,1897,1924]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1761,1786]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,166,1735]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[159,1428,166,1735]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 7. Leucascus simplex (UFRJPOR 6451). A—Specimen in situ. B—Fixed specimen. C—Cross-section of the choanosome. D—Triactine. E—Tetractine. F—Apical actine of two tetractines. Abbreviation: at = atrium; cx = cortex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3698791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3698791/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">Fig 7D</figureCitation>
). Size: 102.5/ 
<quantity box="[1279,1362,1897,1924]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.7" pageId="16" pageNumber="277" unit="mm" value="8.7">8.7 µm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1284,2032]" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis box="[199,322,1934,1959]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">Tetractines</emphasis>
. Regular to sagittal. Actines are slightly conical with sharp tips (
<figureCitation box="[1057,1139,1933,1960]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1761,1786]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,166,1735]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[159,1428,166,1735]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 7. Leucascus simplex (UFRJPOR 6451). A—Specimen in situ. B—Fixed specimen. C—Cross-section of the choanosome. D—Triactine. E—Tetractine. F—Apical actine of two tetractines. Abbreviation: at = atrium; cx = cortex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3698791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3698791/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">Fig 7E</figureCitation>
). The apical actine is very thin (needle-like), cylindrical and sharp, covered with very short spines (
<figureCitation box="[965,1044,1969,1996]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1761,1786]" captionTargetBox="[159,1428,166,1735]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[159,1428,166,1735]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 7. Leucascus simplex (UFRJPOR 6451). A—Specimen in situ. B—Fixed specimen. C—Cross-section of the choanosome. D—Triactine. E—Tetractine. F—Apical actine of two tetractines. Abbreviation: at = atrium; cx = cortex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3698791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3698791/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="277">Fig 7F</figureCitation>
). Size: 96.7/ 
<quantity box="[1191,1271,1969,1996]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.1" pageId="16" pageNumber="277" unit="mm" value="8.1">8.1 µm</quantity>
(basal actine); 72.8/ 
<quantity box="[215,295,2005,2032]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="16" pageNumber="277" unit="mm" value="2.7">2.7 µm</quantity>
(apical actine).
</paragraph>
